`ptr = (node)malloc(sizeof(node));` doesn&#39;t set the *callers* argument; it&#39; sets a local variable. Further, the hiding of pointer types in typedef aliases is only advisable in two conditions (blackbox handle APIs and callback function types), neither of which are your case. That aliasing actually makes your code *harder* to read; not easier. C programmers want to see the asterisks of pointers, no matter how many levels of indirection are involved.

Assuming your node structure looks like this:

    typedef struct NODE {
        int data;
        struct NODE *left;
        struct NODE *right;
    } NODE;

The proper insertion mechanics for a recursive solution would involve declaring the input pointer to be in/out (and therefore a pointer to its type). Since it&#39;s type is already a pointer, that means the proper input argument would be a pointer-to-pointer-to `NODE`. Therefore the resulting function looks like this (sans error checking, which I leave to you):

    void insert(NODE **pp, int value)
    {
        if (!*pp)
        {
            *pp = malloc(sizeof **pp);
            (*pp)-&gt;data = value;
            (*pp)-&gt;left = NULL;
            (*pp)-&gt;right = NULL;
        }
        else if (value &lt; (*pp)-&gt;data) {
            insert(&amp;(*pp)-&gt;left, value);
        }
        else {
            insert(&amp;(*pp)-&gt;right, value);
        }
    }

This does two things:

 1. Fixes your improper pass-by-value usage.
 2. Fixes the undersized allocation you had due to the `node` alias confusion.
 3. Removes the requirement of updating the global `root` (it no longer even has to be global).

Somewhere in `main` you can now do this:

    int main()
    {
        NODE *root = NULL;
        insert(&amp;root, 42);
        insert(&amp;root, 16);
        insert(&amp;root, 91);
        // etc..
    }

It is worthwhile to step through the code provided in a test harness and a debugger, line by line, to see exactly what is transpiring. 


----------

**Iterative Solution**

Using the above technique, you can easily transform that function to be iterative rather than recursive, and eventually you&#39;ll be tasked with that request. It would look like the code below (note the same argument list, and again, sans error checking, which I leave to you):

    void insert(NODE **pp, int value)
    {
        while (*pp)
        {
            if (value &lt; (*pp)-&gt;data)
                pp = &amp;(*pp)-&gt;left;
            else
                pp = &amp;(*pp)-&gt;right;
        }
    
        *pp = malloc(sizeof **pp);
        (*pp)-&gt;data = value;
        (*pp)-&gt;left = NULL;
        (*pp)-&gt;right = NULL;
    }

The code is different, but the setup, and invoke from external caller, is identical.

Hope it helps.

